  <rdf:Description rdf:about="https://scholarlyontology.aueb.gr/resources/so_instances/so_MLE#Method/Palynology_3203916/98_69_84">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="https://scholarlyontology.aueb.gr/resources/so_schema/so_MLE#Method"/>
    <so:method_name>Palynology</so:method_name>
    <so:textual_span>pollen analysis</so:textual_span>
    <so:has_sentence_context rdf:resource="https://scholarlyontology.aueb.gr/resources/so_instances/so_MLE#Sentence/3203916/98"/>
    <so:description>Palynology is the study of microorganisms and microscopic fragments of macroorganisms that are composed of acid-resistant organic material and occur in sediments, sedimentary rocks, and even some metasedimentary rocks. Palynomorphs are the microscopic, acid-resistant organic remains and debris produced by a wide variety of plants, animals, and Protista that have existed since the late Proterozoic.</so:description>
    <so:wikipedia_url>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=328274</so:wikipedia_url>
  </rdf:Description>
  <rdf:Description rdf:about="https://scholarlyontology.aueb.gr/resources/so_instances/so_MLE#Method/Cupellation_3238495/73_119_130">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="https://scholarlyontology.aueb.gr/resources/so_schema/so_MLE#Method"/>
    <so:method_name>Cupellation</so:method_name>
    <so:textual_span>cupellation</so:textual_span>
    <so:has_sentence_context rdf:resource="https://scholarlyontology.aueb.gr/resources/so_instances/so_MLE#Sentence/3238495/73"/>
    <so:description>Cupellation is a refining process in metallurgy in which ores or alloyed metals are heated to very high temperatures and subjected to controlled operations to separate noble metals like gold and silver, from base metals like lead, copper, zinc, arsenic, antimony, or bismuth, in the ore. Cupellation is based on the principle that precious metals typically oxidise or react chemically at much higher temperatures than base metals.</so:description>
    <so:wikipedia_url>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=1608469</so:wikipedia_url>
  </rdf:Description>
